Sun 6 Mar 2022

Today is Day 104 of Phase of Transition to COVID-19 Resilience.

"Here's a question I'd like you to answer."

The church congregation listened in silence as Senior Pastor asks, "When you think of the days being evil, what comes to mind?"

Immediately, I felt a sinking feeling in my soul because I am disturbed about the horrible reports of the most recent news about the war. And I sighed.

So, when Senior Pastor reads Ephesians 5:16, I could feel the biblical truth of the last phrase, "making the most of every opportunity, because the days are evil."

This morning, we prayed especially for those for whom this is a day of deep sadness in the war right now.

Alone in a cafe, as I sat down to self-reflect, I usually would spend a little time to quiet my thoughts and there are some more things for me to reflect on Ephesians 5:15-16 with the perspective that each day could be my last because "my times are in your hands." - Psalm 31:15

"Be very careful, how you live - not as unwise but as wise, making the most of every opportunity, because the days are evil." 
- Ephesians 5:15-16 

Inside the museum, I was totally captivated by this art installation it appeared to be suspended in the air so I gazed in awe at it. It led me to a journey of realizing the impact human activity on the environment and the importance of protecting the rich legacies embodied in the tropics.

So, so impressive.

As always, I am happy that a trip to the museum sure to keep me engaged constructively. (grins)

Wed 2 Mar 2022

Today is Day 100 of Phase of Transition to COVID-19 Resilience.

As I always do each morning after watering my wife's plant, I take a peek inside the empty nest. This morning, I was just thinking in my head.

"Where have all the young birds gone?" 

It's hard to describe the sadness I felt at the sight of the empty nest so my first thoughts were, "They're fully feathered, strong enough to fly so they've to leave the nest because they don't belong in the nest. So they're gone!"

And then my heart stirred because they each have demonstrated a sense of remarkable independence. They deserve to live a born free life and explore their own world. Furthermore, they have demonstrated to me that the one thing they don't do is continue to live with their parents. And so, as I was fascinated by my repeated encounter of the hummingbirds, I've realized there is much to be grateful when I went back in time for a brief moment and remember that when my wife and I were young parents we had concrete plans to inculcate a sense of independence to our children, to which by God's help when they were very little. I am happy and grateful that they each demonstrate a sense of independence that has been meticulously tested and perfected so far. Moreover, they've learned early they couldn't live with us all their lives because they have commitments to their lives after marriage.

My wife's favourite biblical verse to remind her children, "I have no greater joy to hear that my children are living according to the truth." 
- 3 John 1:4

Perhaps it's empty nest syndrome that move me to write this post. 

Hmm...

Sat 26 Feb 2022

Today is Day 96 of Phase of Transition to COVID-19 Resilience.

Inside a shopping mall, I had a moment where I thought to myself, "Now, I'm getting into a Kid-friendly brunch action...so going for some things to make the session slightly more fun for my little guests, including me." 

Hahah... 

I happen to walk pass The Jelly Hearts Cake Shop, so I decided to give it a try and purchase their Tangy Mango; Classical Original & Tempting Cookies. I should said it was my first time buying and I like it because the feeling was fantastic as I served together with the assorted mini cupcakes from Twelve Cupcakes and a little bit of Marshmallow hearts that brought an instant smile on my three guests' faces. 

Satisfied, they each gave a thumb up and once more, exclaimed:
"The cake is cute." - 10 years old
"I love it!" - 6 years old
"Yummy!" - 2 years old

So every few weeks, I'll treat my little guests with fond indulgence. (grins)

Wed 23 Feb 2022

Today is Day 93 of Phase of Transition to COVID-19 Resilience.

To a quick lunch at a nearby Japanese. To me, as usual there's nothing more satisfying than having a healthy bowl of Avocado Salad (S$8.90), that once I start eating, I want to eat more, I can't stop.

I love sharing stories so I thought it would be good to share with you that recently I've received quite a lot of text messages directly from friends and close relatives, through to this morning, and they informed me they're infected with the notorious virus. I took their text messages calmly and matter-of-factly, but it's sobering to know of someone I love is ill.

1."Please uphold us in your prayers my husband is infected and is admitted in KTPH." 
2." CZ recovers from COVID-19 but RZ is still positive." 
3."My FIL, admitted last Fri, diagnosed last Sat.
4."Btw C was tested C+ last Thursday. "
5."I kena Covid."
6."I got COVID-19 from my nephew. I'll be on MC."
7."My classmate positive."

When I closed my eyes, I could conjure up in the exact situations, and I was able to focus on their situations, and the questions in my head: Why is this happening aggressively? When will everything go back to pre-pandemic life?

Finally, and not for the first time, I wish to express my personal thoughts that that's in these uncertain times whenever we feel frustrated, or afraid, or when life turns upside down, or when it feels like everything is falling apart to immediately start praying.

"Be happy in your hope, stand your ground, when you're in trouble, and devote yourselves to prayer." - Roman 12:12

Coincidentally, I fondly remember the late Jane Marczewski, the singer known as Nightbirde who received the golden buzzer from Simon Cowell in Season 16 of AGT in 2021. She once said this words of wisdom, "You can't wait until life isn't hard anymore before you decide to be happy." I love and appreciate it. And I also love her song, "It's Okay" because she writes her own music based on her own personal experience about how she battles with cancer. Unfortunately, she didn't survive the battle.

I share this sentiment entirely in her song it was so touching that it brought tears to my eyes.

Sat 19 Feb 2022

Today is Day 89 of Phase of Transition to COVID-19 Resilience.

The above pictures were displayed in chronological order. One morning, I came upon the two eggs unexpectedly, the mother bird skips a day to lay another egg so it comes as a pleasant surprise, and what happened next is that I saw the young birds hatched out, she raised her young in an amazing way, I saw them grow their wings, and I saw one of them fly away before my eyes.Quickly, I stood still in front of my wife's plant. I moved the twigs and leaves a bit to check if other young birds were around, but what stared back was just an empty nest. 

"It's empty," I announced in sadness and happiness. It's hard to describe the sadness I felt at the sight of the empty nest yet I am very happy by this sight. I've a lot of thoughts and I began to muse about my own past life event about the issues of separation and loss so it's natural for me to have mixed feelings. 

I've taken a lot of pictures because I marveled at the love and great instinct of the mother bird. I also marveled at the baby birds' first minutes of life, in between I was hoping to spot the family in the vicinity of the empty nest. In an instant, I am happy to recognise that the mother bird and her youngs are at a point where they're happiest they all have finally flown off as a family.This encounter with nature and life is a never-to-be-forgotten moment. That's just too amazing to me being right next to them and with them. 

I love the natural world because it was created by God. 

"Ask the animals and they will teach you, or the birds in the sky, and they will tell you, or speak to the earth and it will teach you, or let the fish in the sea inform you. Which of all there does not know that the hand of the Lord has done this? In his hand is the life of every creature and the breath of all mankind."
 - Job 12:7-10

Hopefully, although this was not the first time I'll be highly excited to welcome the third time return of the mother bird when her duty of motherhood calls, in the near future. Jiayou! 加油! (aka Go on! Go for it).

Lor Mee SGD3.5 🇸🇬

Love this new cafe that we found on Sunday after church!!

Old Hen Coffee
127 Owen Rd, Singapore 218931

This place is super cosy and has an open concept kitchen as well and the smell is hooooo

Ordered the Muesli bowl. Crunchy almonds and muesli. Super refreshing with the Greek yoghurt $9.5

Ahi Tuna Salad $15
The salad was good as well. Tuna was fresh. But by the time you finished the muesli, already full.

Ordered others like:
1. Truffle fries 9.90
2. Basil Pistachio Pesto Spaghetti $16.50 really good as well
3. Smoked salmon rosti $17.9 if you like rosti, must try. 
4. Maple bacon mac and cheese $16.50 comes in a hot bowl. 
5. Kombucha! no sugar organic kind. Tried the ginger which was great! 

Loving it!

I tried this pretty amazing all you can eat hotpot buffet! 
Check out full vid in bio!

Guo Fu Hotpot Steamboat! 
20 Cross Street 01-31 Cross Street Exchange, 048422

Firstly it was not very crowded during weekday lunch time so it was nice to have loads of space fo yourself and friends

For lunch buffet, it is $27.90++ per pax 
You need to add on a soup base starting from additional $3.90. Just get the herbal or mala soup.

I am impressed by the quality of the beef and pork. Fatty beef and pork belly are a must get. Also get the veges like watercress, You mai cai, wintermelon and others

They have over 30 items free flow! 

Also includes cooked food like steamed basket of xiao long bao. I must say is superb. Other cooked food like shallot pancake and steamed dumplings. 

Interesting part was that a lady server will go around and serve sauces to each table. Must try are the sesame sauce and they had a minced mushrooms too! 

I think is super worth it for the price and super delicious. 

Farewell lunch.

Decided to head to @manam.sg for a quiet night with love. See our vid blog link in bio: 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G-Fwv1bS5YI

This was a very atas (high end) dining experience at Manam.

Greeted by friendly servers and we felt very welcomed! The restaurant was also very cosy.

“Manam” represents emotion beyond words, and indeed it was, in my honest opinion.

I must say everything was cooked to perfection with the South Indian flavours you expect but mind blown!

𝗪𝗲 𝘁𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗱: 
𝟭) 𝗖𝗿𝗶𝘀𝗽𝘆 𝗢𝗸𝗿𝗮 𝗙𝗿𝘆: 𝗙𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗱 𝗟𝗮𝗱𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗳𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗲𝗿𝘀, 𝘀𝘂𝗽𝗲𝗿 𝗱𝗲𝗹𝗶𝘀𝗵 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗳𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝘀𝗽𝗶𝗰𝗲𝘀! 
𝟮) 𝗡𝗮𝗹𝗹𝗶 𝗘𝗹𝘂𝗺𝗯𝘂 𝗥𝗮𝘀𝗮𝗺: 𝗦𝗽𝗶𝗰𝘆 𝗕𝗿𝗼𝘁𝗵 𝗼𝗳 𝗠𝘂𝘁𝘁𝗼𝗻 𝗦𝘁𝗲𝘄𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗦𝗽𝗶𝗰𝗲𝘀. 
𝟯) 𝗞𝗮𝗿𝘂𝘃𝗲𝗽𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗮𝗶 𝗘𝗿𝗮𝗹 𝗩𝗮𝗿𝘂𝘃𝗮𝗹: 𝗣𝗿𝗮𝘄𝗻𝘀 𝗠𝗮𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗮𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗻 𝗦𝗽𝗶𝗰𝗲𝗱 𝗖𝘂𝗿𝗿𝘆 𝗟𝗲𝗮𝗳 𝗣𝗮𝘀𝘁𝗲 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗖𝗼𝗼𝗸𝗲𝗱 𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗹 𝗧𝗲𝗻𝗱𝗲𝗿. 
𝟰) 𝗩𝗮𝗮𝘇𝗵𝗮𝗶 𝗜𝗹𝗮𝗶 𝗠𝗲𝗲𝗻 𝗩𝗮𝗿𝘂𝘃𝗮𝗹: 𝗙𝗶𝘀𝗵 𝗧𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗰𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝗠𝗮𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗮𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗻 𝗦𝗽𝗶𝗰𝗲𝗱 𝗖𝘂𝗿𝗿𝘆 𝗟𝗲𝗮𝗳 𝗣𝗮𝘀𝘁𝗲, 𝗪𝗿𝗮𝗽𝗽𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗻 𝗕𝗮𝗻𝗮𝗻𝗮 𝗟𝗲𝗮𝗳 
𝟱) 𝗣𝗲𝗽𝗽𝗲𝗿 𝗳𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗱 𝗰𝗵𝗶𝗰𝗸𝗲𝗻: 𝘀𝘂𝗽𝗲𝗿 𝗴𝗼𝗼𝗱 𝗮𝘀 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹 
𝟲) 𝗠𝗮𝗱𝘂𝗿𝗮𝗶 𝗞𝗮𝗿𝗶 𝗧𝗵𝗼𝘀𝗮𝗶: 𝗞𝗮𝗹 𝗧𝗵𝗼𝘀𝗮𝗶 𝗧𝗼𝗽𝗽𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗠𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗲𝗱 𝗖𝗵𝗶𝗰𝗸𝗲𝗻 𝗖𝘂𝗿𝗿𝘆. 
𝟳) 𝗚𝗮𝗿𝗹𝗶𝗰 𝗡𝗮𝗮𝗻 
𝟴) 𝗧𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗲𝗮 𝗶𝗻 𝗽𝗼𝘁 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘀𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗻𝗴

My personal favourite was the Thosai, something very authentic South Indian, not like the Thosai we normally eat.

And the Fried Okra is a must get!
Come here now!

Manam
15 Upper Circular Rd, 01-01, Singapore 058413
Opens Tues-Sun, closed Monday

Hi all and happy Blessed Saturday! May you have a great day with family or whatever you doing.

Starting out morning before church with Indian food.

My church located at Jalan Peminpin so is abit ulu to try this place. But the food court here along the street has super good dosai and chappati.

Total only $2.50

Health tip: instead of eating roti prata, try plain dosai or chapatti. Dosai is made from lentils and chickpeas and is lighter with less calories below 100kcal so it is great option. Chapattis are also great as it is low fat and higher in proteins. Just sharing.

So happy we got to celebrate this festive season with turkey from @parkroyalpickering. Happy because, this is probably one of the best turkeys we have had (two other people we shared the turkey with agreed!). We had the whole turkey at home, so we had the opportunity to try all parts of it - the inner breast, outer breast, thighs, etc. Pleased to report that all parts were extremely tender and juicy. Quite amazed at how evenly roasted this big guy was.

Because we haven’t been able to travel, we have been doing a staycation a month for the past year plus. To date our favourite remains @andazsingapore. Our grading criteria is simplistic though: good view, good service, gorgeous interior, and reasonable price point. Andaz checks all.

On our visit last weekend, we were especially happy that the technical who came to our room removed his shoes at the door, without prompt. Small thing, but big impact (at least for us).

We have been curious if more people pronounce the hotel as “AND-DAZ” or “AUNT-DAZ” (with silent “T”).

We had the 4-course lunch omakase ($88++) earlier today at 1 Michelin Star @rhubarb_le_restaurant. We found the meal to be of value and quality produce. Apart from the four courses, servings of bread, and an amuse bouche, were also served.

Our first course was Sashimi-Grade Scallops topped with caviar, and accompanied with Nashi pear,  and cucumber “sauce”. We love the rather unique and refreshing pairing, which turned out to be sort of the theme for our lunch, as you will see.

Next came the Emulsion of Jerusalem Artichoke with Black Truffle Paste. This was a hit at the table. Full-bodied texture, but rather light flavours to prepare our palate for the main to come.

The beef. Two generous slabs. We did not quite like the sweetness from the dates; we thought the sauce could have been served separately. The meat was quite good though. Slightly overdone and rough at the edges, but otherwise it packed a good bite and chew. There was also a tinge of inherent flavours. Sufficient for the price we are paying.

Dessert was, yet again, unconventional in our books. Blackberry, nata de coco, and lemon - quite a “love it or hate it” one we feel.

The service was good. The space was elegant, albeit a little buzzing, but that’s fine by us. Overall, a restaurant which we appreciate for the atypical French dishes, and one we wouldn’t mind revisiting.

We headed over to @oneninetysg at @fssingapore yesterday for lunch. Well, not exactly the One-Ninety that you may be familiar with, but the whole area next to it, known as Garden@One-Ninety. It is this stunning outdoor (but covered) dining area that was revealed with its new concept earlier this year. We posted it on our personal socials yesterday and it drew a lot of attention, because, well, it is stunning. Swipe to the last of this series to see a short video.

The restaurant offers a la carte menu for lunch. We had a self-assembled three-course meal. Of the starters we had (swipe left), we recommend the David Herve Fine Oysters (No. 3) ($48++/6 pieces). The accompanying ponzu couldn’t go wrong. The Hamachi Tiradito ($32++) was also excellent. It’s essentially thick-cut sashimi, in “ceviche” style - in this case, citrus soy. But we do feel that the price for this was rather steep.

For mains, we had Laksa with Pan-Seared Seabass ($38++) - this we recommend. The laksa had just the right amount of lemak and to our liking. Portion of the fish was huge and extremely fresh. But it was unseasoned. We thought some light seasoning would have been perfect. And oh, a little more laksa broth, please! 

The Wagyu Beef Pho ($45++) tasted on the sweet side, if that is up your alley. Most of the different cuts / types of meats were pretty good. But we still think it was a little pricey.

We will share about the desserts and drinks in a separate post. But simply for the fact that it has the perfect vibes to wind down on a weekend, we foresee ourselves going back. They serve afternoon tea at that space too. We heard that they are teaming up with a certain celebrity florist come January. If the menu and price point look promising, we will head over.

But to dine in this beautiful space, be prepared for pesky flies. It was otherwise not hot, humid, or uncomfortable even though it was outdoors. We think it’s because the adjacent stretch of road is lined with gigantic trees, providing the first layer of shade.

Our celebration of the end of Monday was by way of dinner at @isteaksdiner. It was our first visit, and we tried their Australian Wagyu (Marbling Score 4/5) Stockyard ($49 for 200g). The meat was inherently flavourful, and that was really all we wanted this evening. The fats were only slightly concentrated at a corner. Other than that it was nicely spread out. It packed quite some chew, owing to the medium rare doneness. The cut itself wasn’t the thickest, however. And the bite was not as firm. We prefer firmer bites, but it is not a big complaint. Each steak comes with two sides.

Having a nice chat over tea and cakes.

last weekend :-) 

visited kohi along joochiat; had 😀4😀 cups of coffee ☕️ 
•iced hojicha latte 
•iced white 
•iced mocha 
•iced kohito (signature) 

ngl kohito (first pic), i felt that the coffee was TOO acidic for me (idky) & the added mint leaves was totally not what i want in my coffee. 
hojicha & mocha was decent.. sb was better. 
i liked the iced white a lot, maybe bc the first round (kohito) threw me off😵‍💫 it was smooth, not acidic, slightly bitter & not sweet at all. 

💭(since i tried 4 cups i think they don’t rly add sugar cuz it has little to no sweetness._.) 
(u can change normal milk to soy/oat milk)😃 

kohi has a rly cool initiative: a hole in the wall, only accepts gratitudes so u can put any amt of $ (tips) u wanna OR u can have ur coffee free! i kinda like this concept of outdoor grab n go but the queue was kinda long and waiting time to get my coffee was a little long too (they only had 2 people making coffee!) 
i wld come back for a quick coffee fix (iced white) but if i’m looking for good quality coffee, i’ll probably get others.

today at rockymaster 

• iced hazel-notti latté 🌰 
• iced cafe latté ☕️ 
• al funghi 🍄 
• teriyaki chicken 🐓 
• mushroom soup 🥣 
• ondeh ondeh cake 🍰 

decent cup of iced cafe latté, not too shabby and bitter, slightly on the sweeter side. i don’t mind it thou. but the hazel-notti latté thou… TOO sweet. lacked coffee taste. 🥴 

both the pastas were decent, not too bad; just like what you wld expect for a decent plate of pasta. teriyaki was slightly too sweet but it’s still ok. erm the mushroom soup was thick but tasted like chicken soup??? as me & my fren took a couple mouths of it it wasn’t that bad- was able to finish the entire bowl. 
i gotta say thou lmao the ondeh ondeh cake might as well just name it as pandan cake lmao cuz all we tasted was pandan. zero gula melaka taste at all. cream was damn sweet but fortunately the cake itself was moist and not flaky. 

i have no idea why everything is so sweet here but maybe it’s the concept they were going for lmao. i was introduced by a fren to RM for coffee but i guess it’s pretty decent, would rather sb than this (since price wise roughly the same) 🙂

also: ty fren for visiting w me✨🤍

stuff slaps ngl 

•lemon curd tart🤍🍋 @skinnycakes.sg 
so gUd. lemon is actually a little sour but once the sweet curd hits, 💯. nice lightly torched curd bring forth the smoky flavor in your mouth. the tart itself is just right in texture, hardness, breaks apart but doesn’t crumble into smaller pieces. 

it’s been my fav lemon tart in sg (so far)🥺
how i got to know skinny cakes- my fren ordered a super pretty raspberry rose cream cheese birthday cake for me (pls try it out!) and i was SO mindblowned 💨 by the quality, flavor and texture hence 💁🏻‍♀️ 
find me another better lemon tart & we’ll talk. 😵‍💫

So happy for @twobakeboys 🥺❤️known them since their Homebaker days! Congratulations on your first cafe space✨ housed inside Rest Hotel Bugis 👍 it’s like the start of Singapore’s version of Afteryou cafe 🌸 
…
They have simple brunch menu for now like their breakfast plate and some added desserts: CROFFLES WITH ICE CREAM 💯 and of cos their usual cakes with wider selection of their Thai inspired gelatos are also available ☺️✨ will definitely be back as it’s really cosy spot with both indoor and outdoor dining 😍 all the best kitty and do support her husband’s coffee ☕️😂 barista-in-training💪

Didn’t realised @goldenbrownhambaga is hidden inside @akashi.sg at @paragon.sg 😯✨ and this raved tamago yaki hambaga ($10.80) is considered DESSERT??? Super thick tamago katsu!!! It’s pretty sweet but still with a savory node from the dashi 😊 together with the fluffy brioche bun, it’s heavier than it looks - best shared as it can get quite intense for one😶

A new addition is their Summer Unagi Bata Roll ($18.80) which is filled Charcoal grilled summer unagi with Akashi's 25yrs secret unagi sauce, hand cut cucumber, TOO MUCH BUTTER in the brioche roll. The Unagi is yums but why use pure unsalted butter in clunks inside - it’s like eating frozen butter😅🧈 
…
💡: the tamago burger is at a decent price point for share 👍 I do like the katsu batter and sweet tamago but the unagi, as much as it’s seasoned well - the use of butter is a no no. Sinful max. For $18.80, would like bit more unagi please🥲

Ranked as one of the best Italian restaurants in Singapore on Tripadvisor, Rosso Vino focuses on authentic traditional Italian classics like pastas and pizzas. For starters, we were thoroughly impressed with the Zuppa di Mare ($22), a mixed seafood soup that has prawns, calamari, clams, and mussels, and served with a toasted bread. The soup was appetizing and flavourful, perfect to whet your appetite for the mains. We didn’t waste a single drop of the soup and ordered more of the grilled bread with garlic butter to mop up all of it.

For the mains, we shared the Fettucine Bolognese ($25), a homemade pasta with slow-cooked minced beef sauce with Parmesan cheese and the Penne al Tartufo e Funghi Porcini ($28), a highly recommended pasta dish of penne cooked in a rich and aromatic truffle cream sauce with porcini mushrooms. If you are there for a date night or as a group gathering, it will be great to order a few pastas to share so that you can try most of the flavours. When you see a dish with the restaurant’s name on it, it is an indication that it is something that you should try, and that is exactly what we got with the Calzone Rosso Vino ($30), a folded pizza stuffed with tomato sauce, mozzarella, pork ham and mushrooms. This is not like your typical pizza but one with a doughy consistency that will fill you up quick.

For dessert, it has to be the Tiramisu ($17), a traditional Italian dessert made with ladyfingers’ biscuits, layered with mascarpone cheese, and soaked in espresso coffee. A decadent finish to the meal before washing it all down with the Spritz Cocktail ($16), concocted with Aperol, prosecco, soda water and finished with an orange wedge. 
•••••••••••••••••••
✨ Rosso Vino
📍 15 Merbau Road, Singapore 239032
🌐 https://www.rossovinosingapore.com/

Nando’s is no stranger to many with their famed flame-grilled PERi-PERi chicken and one of the dining destinations for great value and affordable meals with nett pricing and no service charge. The chicken are freshly grilled-to-order, cooked to juicy perfection and what makes Nando’s stand out is the PERi-PERi spices that they coat onto the chicken, which is a unique blend of African bird’s eye chilli.

The signature order for most will be the ¼ chicken with 2 sides ($15.90) and you can choose the varying spice heat levels from plain to lemon & herb to extra hot for the hotheads. You can pair the grilled chicken with sides such as PERi-PERi chips and corn-on-the-cob. What is unique in the Singapore’s menu are the PERi-PERi bowls that you can customize and build your own bowl with the accompanying sides that have been infused with Asian flavours. What I got is with two boneless thighs over a base of PERi-PERi Noodles ($14.90), which is our mee tai mak but in a PERi-Laksa sauce. The laksa might be slightly mild in terms of the flavour as it was to cater to the masses. I added on the Asian Slaw ($2) and Grilled Broccoli ($3) to complete the meal.
•••••••••••••••••••
✨ Nando’s
📍 200 Victoria Stret, Bugis Junction, Unit 01-85/87, Singapore 188021
🌐 https://order.nandos.com.sg/#/

Goldenroy just did another pizza homerun with their newest addition of the Spongebob’s Revenge: Browned Butter Scallops with Onions ($34). Having previously tasted all of their other pizzas, including the favourite Clam & Garlic Sourdough, this new seafood sourdough pizza definitely ranks high up with it. Whoever or whatever that made Spongebob angry for him to create this revenge pizza definitely did the right thing as the plump and juicy scallops are a joy to eat, and pairs perfectly with the large cuts of onion. The pizza is made with a crispy sourdough base over a tomato sauce and topped with all these ingredients.

Roy’s favourite has also been upgraded with the Mushroom Pesto Sourdough ($26) now in version 2 and is even more moreish with the earthy mushrooms that complements with the richness of the cheese and pesto sauce. Not forgetting the addictive Sourdough Garlic Knots ($10) that has been aged for 48 hours, this snack is baked in olive oil, filled with rare cheese, glazed with garlic butter, and topped with freshly shave aged Parmesan. To sweeten the deal, add-on the Sourdough Garlic Knots to enjoy free delivery with a minimum pizza order of $45.

The Jelebu Dry Laksa pop-up at Takeshi Noodle Bar will be extended till May 2022, and this is a hidden gem for a dining experience of modern twist on local dishes. Don’t wait too long, quickly make a reservation (link below) and try out some of Chef Renée’s dishes today!

Before diving into the signature seafood dry laksa, order up a few small plates that you can share with the group. There is the Scallop & Otah Pillow (3pcs, $22) that we have tried which was an explosion of flavour and texture, made with a nori cracker base, topped with otah mousse, hokkiado scallops and avruga caviar for that extra indulgence. Another dish that might be polarizing between diners is the Marmite Brussels Sprouts ($14), which we absolutely love and wiped the plate clean. The umami-ness and richness from the Marmite aioli complements well with the slight bitterness from the brussels sprouts, making it a very addictive vegetable to munch on. To add on to the texture, Chef Renée has added tempura enoki and pickled purple cabbage to balance the flavours. The Szechuan on a Stick (2pcs, $14) marries different cultures into a single dish with the grilled pepper pork satay having a nice sauce bath of the nam jim jaew and finished with crunchy peanuts.

The headliner has definitely got to be the Jelebu Dry Laksa, which we got with the grilled tiger prawn ($22) or you can bougie it up by getting it with the butter-poached lobster ($32/$46). The laksa does not come with your usual thick bee hoon, but a specially formulated one that is able to latch onto the laksa sauce very well so that in every slurp you will get the maximum taste possible. What truly shines through is the housemade rempah that has been blended with all aromatics and spices, and every ingredient such as the taupok, fishcakes, beansprouts and cockles all complement each other well.
•••••••••••••••••••
✨ Jelebu Dry Laksa
📍 12 Teck Lim Road, Takeshi Noodle Bar, Singapore 088387

Pao fan has been the trend in recent times with many brands popping up frequently. One brand that stood out is San Pin Pao Fan 三品泡饭, which has several outlets across the island. What I like about their pao fan is that when you order takeaway/delivery, the broth, fried egg floss and crispy rice crisps are packed separately so that you can have a great experience dining at home. You can simply just put the rice into the paper bowl, pour in the broth before adding the fried egg floss and rice crisps. In addition, what is great about San Pin Pao Fan 三品泡饭 is that they have variety of options from the Mixed Pao Fan to Iberico Sliced Pork Pao Fan, together with a limited number of side dishes like fried mid joint wings to go along with your rice. For pao fan, one of the key factors is the broth itself and the orange-hued broth here has the right amount of seafood flavour, body and umami-ness without being too surfeited.
•••••••••••••••••••

🍵Iced Classic Matcha Latte - An Easy Recipe! 

Make this easy Iced Matcha Latte just like your favorite cafe. If you’re missing your usual iced matcha latte from Starbucks or your neighborhood cafe, this recipe is for you! As a result, you’ll be able to make your favorite drink at home!

Ingredients 
2 teaspoons matcha powder
50ml hot water
1 teaspoon honey
Ice
150g Milk of choice (I used soy milk)

Naoki Matcha have been in Singapore since 2020, with specialty is curating blends of matcha from different tea regions of Japan – each tailored to different use case and preferences. Find them on naokimatcha.asia, Shopee.sg and Lazada.sg.

Naoki Matcha’s Superior Blend is made from Uji, the home to Japanese matcha culture and high quality matcha products. Taste wise, slightly bittersweet taste with fresh aroma from the matcha blend. Thumbs up to its premium quality matcha powder. 

Unsweetened by default and sweetness level is customisable and you can choose iced or hot. Create your matcha latte at home, visit Naoki Matcha's Shopee store at http://shor.by/shp_naokimatcha_sup to get yours now!

The most common diet myth is eat less can lose weight.🧐

Eating less doesn't cause fat loss as it doesn't prompt the need to burn body fat.

Try not to choose food over another just because it is lower in calories, because the lower calories food might have lack of nutrients as compared to a meal that has slightly higher calories.

Healthy food is the way to go and cleaning up your diet is the #1 thing to do right now!

Maldives portrait photo dump - TIPS part 2 🏖 

- Most resorts will probably include all 3 meals, some include only certain meals so remember to see if you need to top up. Ours included daily buffet BLD by default, realised it’s been a long time since I could actually self service for my buffet 🥲
- For us we opted for an island resort 400km away from Male airport because it is about half of what a normal resort costs. Also it has a 5 star TripAdvisor rating and 9.2 on booking.com so I chose to suffer the traveling time. I read that the reefs are nicer and less bleached the further they are from the city. My priority was good snorkeling. Flight and boat wait times were quite painful but you will forget the pain. I booked directly with resort because you know turbulent times.
- Decide if you want a beach or overwater villa. Most people try to experience both in one trip but I only wanted to go Maldives just so I could experience the latter. 
- If you are (ironically) afraid of too much sun like me, you can pack your activities in the morning and evening because afternoon is way too hot
- Check out my ig stories or TikTok if you want to see more videos 
- You don’t need a sim card because the resorts will offer wifi although very patchy (justifiable given the seclusion). roaming for SingTel or StarHub doesn’t cover Maldives

How do vegan sushis taste like? Last weekend, we tried @sautesushi, the 1st plant-based sushi train restaurant in Singapore. 🍃🍃🍃⁣
⁣
The Volcano Lava (S$13.90++) is made up of thinly sliced carrots, cucumbers, and crispy bits, wrapped around layers of sushi rice and seaweed, satisfying on every bite. The roll is served with generous amount of spicy vegan mayo. So, if you’re a fan of spicy food, you’d love this. And how can we not love Abi Avocado (S$12.90++)? The fillings were crispy, topped with creamy avocado and mayo.⁣
⁣
These two dishes are in “Singapore’s 50 Best Vegan Dishes Award” by @abillion. ⁣
⁣
@abillion is a plant-based review platform where members can review plant-based dishes and products. ⁣

description:
📍Sarnies

had an EGG-licious brunch last weekend! 🍳😋

𝐄𝐠𝐠𝐬 𝐁𝐞𝐧-𝐉𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐧 ($21) 

the stunning visual is enough to make anyone’s mouth water 😍 and it tastes as good as it looks! glorious poached eggs doused in creamy 𝗯𝗲𝗮𝗿𝗻𝗮𝗶𝘀𝗲 sat atop a bed of soft 𝘄𝗶𝗹𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝘀𝗽𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗰𝗵 and sweet-savoury meat flavoured with 𝗯𝗮𝗰𝗼𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗷𝗮𝗺. topped with crispy 𝗵𝗼𝗺𝗲-𝗰𝘂𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗯𝗮𝗰𝗼𝗻 that was on the drier side and not too salty which i preferred! the toasted english muffin buns were airy and held the saucy components well without turning soggy. the only pity is that the poached eggs were overcooked and not runny 😢 

𝐎𝐦𝐞𝐥𝐞𝐭𝐭𝐞 ($18) 

this HUGE and luscious omelette was bursting with flavours from the generous amount of melted cheesy 𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱𝗱𝗮𝗿, fragrant 𝘀𝗮𝘂𝘁𝗲𝗲𝗱 𝗺𝘂𝘀𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗼𝗺𝘀 and 𝘀𝗼𝗳𝘁 𝗼𝗻𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀. 🧀🧄 the 𝗿𝘆𝗲 𝘀𝗼𝘂𝗿𝗱𝗼𝘂𝗴𝗵 𝘁𝗼𝗮𝘀𝘁 had a slight tang which nicely balanced out the savouriness but it was a tad tough to cut through. 

overall the food was pretty good and totally satisfied my love for eggs! 😋🍳 price is kinda steep but it was worth with Burpple 1 for 1 deal ✨ 

#eggsbenedict #omelette #brunch

📍Thekneadhouse 🏠 

looking for some 𝗵𝗼𝗺𝗲𝗺𝗮𝗱𝗲 𝘀𝗻𝗮𝗰𝗸𝘀 to perk up your day? 🌼 check out @thekneadhouse.sg for decadent 𝗻𝘂𝘁𝗲𝗹𝗹𝗮 𝘁𝗮𝗿𝘁𝘀 and crunchy 𝗳𝗹𝗼𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗲𝘀! all hand-baked with love by the sweet and talented @emeliafooddiary 🥰 

𝐍𝐮𝐭𝐞𝐥𝐥𝐚 𝐓𝐚𝐫𝐭𝐬 

a classic snack that is really well-executed! the firm cookie tart base is not too crumbly or hard and has a melt-in-your-mouth texture. it also has a light buttery fragrance that pairs perfectly with the rich and chocolatey Nutella topping. 🍫 i like that it is overall not too sweet which makes it so easy to gobble up a few of these indulgent treats in one shot 😛 

𝐅𝐥𝐨𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬

a new found favourite snack - pastry/biscuit made with almonds, nuts, sunflower seeds, pumpkin seeds, oats (and more) all held together with melted honey, and baked to a perfect crisp. 😮‍💨😍 strong nutty aroma comes from the toasted almond flakes and natural sweetness from the seeds and honey. it is also VERY CRUNCHY and ADDICTIVE 🙌🏼 i guarantee you can’t stop at one! 

overall, i really enjoyed these goodies and they’re so perfect for snacking in the upcoming Chinese New Year 😋 it’s amazing how the bakes do not contain added sugar and still taste so good! 😌💯

thank you @thekneadhouse.sg for letting me try your bakes! ❤️

#nutellatart #florentinecookies #homebasedsg

📍Kanada-Ya [invited]

🍜 𝘀𝗽𝗲𝗰𝗶𝗮𝗹𝗶𝘀𝘁𝘀 𝗶𝗻 𝗮𝘂𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗰 𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗸𝗼𝘁𝘀𝘂 𝗿𝗮𝗺𝗲𝗻 ✨ crowned as No. 1 Ramen restaurant in London 🇬🇧, this famed ramen joint has opened its doors in our little island with 5 outlets! 

𝐒𝐩𝐢𝐜𝐲 𝐘𝐮𝐳𝐮 𝐑𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐧 ($19.90)

interesting fusion of flavours that packed a punch - refreshing and tangy yuzu 🍋 notes that cut through the saltiness of the creamy broth and a spicy 🌶 kick to end it off. each flavour profile was well-balanced without overpowering the other and i enjoyed this novel taste. 

the tender pork chashu were deliciously marinated and the ramen egg is simply perfect 👌🏼 love the chewy al-dente wheat noodles that were slurpy with the thick broth too!

𝐓𝐨𝐧𝐤𝐨𝐭𝐬𝐮 𝐌𝐢𝐱 𝐑𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐧 ($17.90)

if you are looking for a lighter option for your palate, Kanada-Ya offers this soup base which is a blend of rich tonkotsu (pork bone) broth and savoury chicken paitan broth. 🍜 this blend was bursting with a meaty umami flavour and the belly chashu slices had the right amount of lean and fatty parts without too much of a porky taste. 

𝐖𝐚𝐬𝐚𝐛𝐢 𝐌𝐚𝐲𝐨 𝐆𝐲𝐨𝐳𝐚 ($6.90) 

lightly pan-fried and topped with wasabi mayo and nori strips. 🥟 not a fan of wasabi but this was surprisingly palatable as the sharp wasabi taste was quite mild amidst the savoury mayo. 

overall, we enjoyed the hearty and comforting bowls of ramen and the standard is really close to those authentic ones in Japan! 🇯🇵

thank you @kanadaya.sg for the invite and hospitality! 🥰 

#ramen #tonkotsu

📍Sando

the hunt for 𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗖𝗞 𝗚𝗢𝗨𝗥𝗠𝗘𝗧 𝗦𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗪𝗜𝗖𝗛𝗘𝗦🥪 continues and this time i tried @sandosingapore’s highly raved SANDOitchi (サンドイッチ)! 🤩 

𝐘𝐮𝐳𝐮 𝐘𝐚𝐤𝐢-𝐭𝐨𝐫𝐢 ($10) 

this thicc 𝘆𝘂𝘇𝘂 𝗽𝗲𝗽𝗽𝗲𝗿 𝗺𝗮𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗮𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝗰𝗵𝗶𝗰𝗸𝗲𝗻 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗴𝗵 was grilled to juicy and tender with a smoky yakitori aroma and balanced with light citrusy notes from the yuzu. 😍 there were some fatty parts and un-chewable tendons in the meat but not too much to fuss about. 

the 𝗳𝘂𝗿𝗶𝗸𝗮𝗸𝗲 𝗴𝗮𝗿𝗹𝗶𝗰 𝗮𝗶𝗼𝗹𝗶 added a nice dimension to the savoury chargrill flavour of the chicken. paired with an over-easy egg, smashed avocado, tomatoes and lettuce, this sandwich is hearty yet at the same time surprisingly light on the palatte. 

finally, the slightly sweet 𝗯𝘂𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗯𝗿𝗶𝗼𝗰𝗵𝗲 𝗯𝘂𝗻𝘀 were soft, pillowy, toasted perfectly to a golden brown and not too oily. 😋

𝐏𝐨𝐫𝐤 𝐊𝐚𝐭𝐬𝐮 ($10) 

the classic Japanese sando - who can resist those thick slabs of crispy pork loin? 🤤 

the deep-fried panko-breaded batter was exceptionally fragrant but it was soggy when i ate it as i had left the sandwich out for about 1.5hr and the charitable amount of sauce has soaked through the katsu. 🥺 (lesson learnt, always eat your sando fresh off the grill!) 

nonetheless, it was still delish and i love the interplay of the salty, tangy 𝗯𝘂𝗹𝗹𝗱𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗮𝘂𝗰𝗲 and sweet 𝗱𝘂𝗰𝗸 𝗰𝗼𝗻𝗳𝗶𝘁 𝗼𝗻𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀. 💯 the pork loin was a lean cut, firm with a nice bite to it. despite its look, the meat is not too dry or tough. 

💸 pretty worth for the generous and filling portion 👍🏼 the only gripe is the location which is a bit out of the way at the industrial area of Labrador Park but i’ll definitely come back for their breakfast sandos!! 🥪☀️

#sando #sandwich

📍Eleven Strands

finally checked 𝙩𝙝𝙚 highly-raved green pasta from @elevenstrands off my list and it really lives up to the hype! 🙌🏼

𝐏𝐫𝐚𝐰𝐧 𝐁𝐚𝐬𝐢𝐥 𝐏𝐞𝐬𝐭𝐨 𝐏𝐚𝐬𝐭𝐚 ($24) 

the showstopper is definitely the fragrant 𝗯𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗹 𝗽𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗼 𝘀𝗮𝘂𝗰𝗲 🌿 it was very well executed and i love the harmony of flavours - herby and garlicky with a tantalising nuttiness from the crushed pine nuts. the parmesan cheese also adds a nice savoury creaminess without overpowering the earthly aroma of basil. 

the linguine was cooked to al dente with a nice springy chew to it 🤩 every bit of the linguine was coated with the generous amount of pesto sauce so it was really flavourful. it did get a bit oily towards the end but not to the point of surfeiting. 

the diced grilled prawns 🍤 were plentiful, plump and succulent. they also tasted very fresh which is a major plus point. 👍🏼

my friend got the 𝐖𝐚𝐠𝐲𝐮 𝐁𝐞𝐞𝐟 & 𝐒𝐚𝐮𝐬𝐚𝐠𝐞 ($23). i tried the beef patty and it was really juicy and tender! not too fatty either. the sweetness from the caramelised onions and the red wine sauce pair the savoury meat really well. 😋

💸 got this with Burpple 1 for 1 and it amounts to about $15 per person, which is super worth for the quality and portion! 

#pesto #basil #pasta

[Verdict: Terryfic 👍🏻] You can’t go wrong with the 𝘼𝙣𝙙𝙧𝙚𝙬 𝙇𝙤𝙗𝙨𝙩𝙚𝙧 安德鲁龙虾 ($88) at @yangmingseafood. Essentially steamed Boston lobster with soy sauce, fried garlic and cheung fun/ rice noodle rolls. I don’t usually like eating lobster but this is a chef’s kiss. 

Call this an atas (upmarket) rendition of our favourite breakfast staple. I’ve eyeballed this place for quite a while so I’m glad I paid a visit. 

The way it’s cooked brings out the freshness of the crustacean. When biting into the lobster meat, you’ll love it for how soft and sweet it is. I don’t even realise that I’m eating lobster as the claw tastes more like crab. 

Pair it with the silky sheets of cheung fun that’s buried underneath a bed of fragrant, umami soy sauce to satisfy your carb intake. The type of soy sauce plays an important role in giving it its intended flavour. 

You can opt for a more premium lobster if you wish. I’ll post the other dishes I had progressively.
.
#eaterries
location: 扬名海鲜 Yang Ming Seafood

description:
[COCONUT DRINK SERIES 🥥] Going cuckoo with @kookoonut.sg coconut drinks. We tried 15 varieties of shakes and sodas. So here’s a brief summary.

We got all our drinks at 0% sugar level. In fact, the shakes already taste sweet at this level as there’s already sugar in them.

My favourite would be none other than the [Verdict: Terryfic 👍🏻] 𝙊𝙧𝙞𝙜𝙞𝙣𝙖𝙡 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($4.70/5.70). Expect a shake that’s rich in coconut taste. Expect it to be slightly nutty and sweet with chunky bits of coconut flesh as they use fresh young coconuts from Thailand. To make it creamier and milkier, get the 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝙂𝙚𝙡𝙖𝙩𝙤 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($5.50/6.50) that comes with a scoop of coconut gelato. 

I would say the avocado flavour in the [Verdict: SatisfacTerry ✌🏻] 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝘼𝙫𝙤𝙘𝙖𝙙𝙤 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($5.50/6.50) takes the back seat with the coconut flavour being more prominent. This was also the case with [Verdict: SatisfacTerry ✌🏻] 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝙈𝙖𝙩𝙘𝙝𝙖 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($5.20/6.20). Some of you may like the [Verdict: SatisfacTerry ✌🏻] 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝙊𝙧𝙚𝙤 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($4.90/5.90). 

There are interesting flavours such as [Verdict: SatisfacTerry ✌🏻] 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝙋𝙖𝙣𝙙𝙖𝙣 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($4.90/5.90), the tropical tasting [Verdict: SatisfacTerry ✌🏻] 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝙋𝙞𝙣𝙖 𝘾𝙤𝙡𝙖𝙙𝙖 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($5.50/6.50) and the tart [Verdict: InTerrysting 👌🏻] 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝙎𝙤𝙪𝙧𝙨𝙤𝙥 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($5.20/6.20).

The [Verdict: InTerrysting 👌🏻] 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙪𝙩 𝙀𝙨𝙥𝙧𝙚𝙨𝙨𝙤 𝙎𝙝𝙖𝙠𝙚 ($5.90/6.90) is great for caffeine addicts who would appreciate a coffee flavoured shake.

If you like to fizz things up a little, go for their fizzy series that’s made with Thai soda water, coconut juice and flavoured syrup. Choose from [Verdict: SatisfacTerry ✌🏻] 𝙁𝙞𝙯𝙯𝙮 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤 𝙇𝙮𝙘𝙝𝙚𝙚, 𝙁𝙞𝙯𝙯𝙮 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤 𝙆𝙞𝙬𝙞, 𝙁𝙞𝙯𝙯𝙮 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤 𝙇𝙖𝙜𝙤𝙤𝙣 𝙋𝙖𝙧𝙖𝙙𝙞𝙨𝙚 𝙖𝙣𝙙 𝙁𝙞𝙯𝙯𝙮 𝘾𝙤𝙘𝙤 𝙒𝙖𝙩𝙚𝙧𝙢𝙚𝙡𝙤𝙣 ($4.50/5.50). I would prefer the shakes over the soda as the flavoured syrup masks the sweetness of coconut water.

If you’re purist when it comes to coconut shakes, stick to the OG.
.
#eaterries

You can get your fresh seafood supplies from online seafood store @wholefish.sg that’s delivered to your door step. Vacuum packed to maintain its freshness, you can opt to have your fish just the way you want it - scaled, fillet, deboned and sliced.

So I got some fish to share with my family. Here’s what I got 𝘾𝙝𝙞𝙣𝙚𝙨𝙚 𝙋𝙤𝙢𝙛𝙧𝙚𝙩, 𝙈𝙪𝙖𝙧 𝘾𝙝𝙪𝙣𝙠𝙮 𝙁𝙞𝙨𝙝 𝙊𝙩𝙖𝙝, 𝙎𝙚𝙖 𝘽𝙖𝙨𝙨 (𝘽𝙖𝙧𝙧𝙖𝙢𝙪𝙣𝙙𝙞) and 𝘾𝙤𝙙. There’s also a range of seafood such as crabs, prawns, crawfish and squid to choose from. The fish were fresh and meaty. You won’t regret it.

If you’re looking to have a hotpot with your friends and family, you can also get all your hotpot essentials from Whole Fish - meat, vegetables, soup bases and more.

In case you didn’t know, they also sell frozen dim sum from supper hotspot Swee Choon. How convenient can it get!

[PROMO] Y’all can enjoy a 10% discount off your total order from now till 31 March. Use the promo code <10EATERRIES>. 
.
#eaterries

[Verdict: Terryfic 👍🏻] I seldom eat 𝙇𝙖𝙠𝙨𝙖 at most places. But I thought I should try one of the more popular stalls at Marsiling Mall besides the usual suspects of seafood soup, cheung fun and roasted meat. I thought for $4 the serving is already very satisfying. If you’re very hungry, there’s the $5 option on offer. 

Dig into a rich and creamy broth that’s made from coconut milk, dried shrimp, chillies and lemongrass. It’s mildly spicy and acceptable to the average Singaporean palette. A scoop of umami, piquant sambal belacan is added for that additional oomph. 

They don’t scrimp on ingredients here. You’ll get a couple of pieces of cockles (hum), half a boiled egg, beancurd puffs/ tau pok, fish cakes and a bit of laksa leaves for garnish. 

One can understand it’s popularity. They don’t cut corners and is reasonably flavourful considering there’s less coconut milk than the full bodied Katong laksa. 

They also do prawn noodles, pork rib noodles and lor mee. I shall try those next time. 

📍Ye Lai Xiang Laksa
4 Woodlands Street 12
01-73, Marsiling Mall Food Centre
Singapore 738623
.
#eaterries

[NEW] We enjoyed our brunch at @coexistcoffee.co latest outlet at Paya Lebar. So here’s a round up of their savoury items we got to try on the menu. It’s a big and beautiful space. When you step into this airy space, you may just forget that you’re actually in Singapore.

The pastas are pretty enjoyable. Our dining party enjoyed the [Verdict: Terryfic 👍🏻] 𝙀𝙗𝙞𝙠𝙤 𝙇𝙞𝙣𝙜𝙪𝙞𝙣𝙚 ($24) for its heady, umami flavour. Loads of ebiko (seasoned prawn roe) and grilled prawns prawns sit atop the al dente cooked pasta. We also loved the earthy fragrance of the [Verdict: InTerrysting 👌🏻] 𝙈𝙪𝙨𝙝𝙧𝙤𝙤𝙢 𝙍𝙞𝙜𝙖𝙩𝙤𝙣𝙞 ($20) that comes with a medley of mushrooms including button and shiitake mushrooms. 

What got me hooked were the [Verdict: Terryfic 👍🏻] 𝘿𝙞𝙧𝙩𝙮 𝙏𝙖𝙩𝙚𝙧 𝙏𝙤𝙩𝙨 ($16). The addition of minced braised pork and pork jus just brings this humble fried potatoes to a next level. 

Taking our humble breakfast snack a notch up is the [Verdict: Terryfic 👍🏻] 𝘾𝙖𝙧𝙧𝙤𝙩 𝘾𝙖𝙠𝙚 𝙁𝙧𝙞𝙚𝙨 ($14). Drizzled with sambal mayo and chye poh/ pickled radish, it’s crisp on the outside yet soft on the inside. 

We loved the delicious [Verdict: Terryfic 👍🏻] 𝙎𝙦𝙪𝙞𝙙 𝙄𝙣𝙠 𝙍𝙞𝙨𝙤𝙩𝙩𝙤 ($28) that had a local spin to it with the addition of hae bee hiam. You’ll get pieces of firefly squid and crab meat that’s mixed within the briny, creamy rice. 

There’s also pizzas on Fridays to Sundays. We had the all-time classic [Verdict: InTerrysting 👌🏻] 𝙈𝙖𝙧𝙜𝙝𝙚𝙧𝙞𝙩𝙖 ($18) that uses a homemade tomato sauce as its base. It’s not your trending Neapolitan pizza and felt more like a Sicilian pizza as its much thicker.

If you want to feel healthy, there’s the [Verdict: InTerrysting 👌🏻] 𝙂𝙧𝙞𝙡𝙡𝙚𝙙 𝙋𝙚𝙖𝙧 𝙎𝙖𝙡𝙖𝙙 ($26). A simple mix of mesclun, grilled Peckham pear slices, cherry tomatoes and prosciutto crudo before being dressed in balsamic vinaigrette.  As for the [Verdict: InTerrysting 👌🏻] 𝘾𝙖𝙪𝙡𝙞𝙛𝙡𝙤𝙬𝙚𝙧 𝙬𝙞𝙩𝙝 𝘽𝙖𝙩𝙩𝙪𝙩𝙤 𝘿𝙧𝙚𝙨𝙨𝙞𝙣𝙜 ($16) that feels like I’m eating a cauliflower steak.

Look out for my next review on their coffee and desserts. 
.
#eaterries

𝐎𝐲𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐌𝐞𝐞 𝐒𝐮𝐚 - $𝟗.𝟖𝟎
I tried this and it was not bad I guess. There was quite a generous portion of oysters and the broth had a decent umami flavour. You can add the vinegar yourself so you can control how sour it is which is great as I personally don’t like too much vinegar 😬

𝐁𝐫𝐚𝐢𝐬𝐞𝐝 𝐏𝐨𝐫𝐤 𝐑𝐢𝐜𝐞 - $𝟗
My friend got this and he said it was alright but not the best oops. 
―
Saw this place online and decided to give it a try since it is quite near and in the west. I guess the main comparison will be eat 3 bowls which is the well known Taiwanese place which I have tried and reviewed as well. Unfortunately, I think the food here was quite disappointing compared to eat3bowls, the portions were slightly bigger but it is alot pricier than eat3bowls also. :(

📍 Outram Park
▸
𝐃𝐮𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐧 𝐌𝐨𝐮𝐬𝐬𝐞 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐝𝐨𝐮𝐛𝐥𝐞 𝐬𝐡𝐨𝐭 - $𝟔.𝟓𝟎
The special thing about this gelato place is that they have a variety of durian desserts which is always welcome for a durian lover for me 😩 Tried this durian mousse with double D24 shot and I absolutely loved it. It was so rich and creamy and you can definitely tell it is made with good quality authentic durian. The only thing I wish was different was if they used MSW durian instead of D24 but this was still really good! 😮‍💨
―
It is pretty rare for western gelato places to have desserts like durian mousse but I really like their selection of durian desserts! I also tried my friend’s pistachio gelato and it was pretty solid as well. Definitely will be back to try their MSW gelato next time!

𝟒/𝟓

description:
📍 Farrer Park
▸
𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐠𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐚 - $𝟏𝟓 
San Marzano Tomato, Fior di Latte, Pecorino, Basil, Olive Oil
Really liked this thin crust pizza and the cheese was really smooth and not excessive. A solid classic. :)
―
𝐏𝐞𝐩𝐩𝐞𝐫𝐨𝐧𝐢 - $𝟏𝟖
San Marzano Tomato, Pepperoni, Mozzarella, Grana Padano, Chilli, Honey
The same tomato base as the Margherita but with different types of cheeses and a HUGE portion of pepperoni. I really liked the pepperoni, it was slightly charred and was really flavourful. This was probably my favourite pizza of the bunch! 🤤
―
𝐓𝐫𝐮𝐟𝐟𝐥𝐞 𝐌𝐮𝐬𝐡𝐫𝐨𝐨𝐦 - $𝟏𝟖.𝟓𝟎
Portobello, Bechamel, Onion, Mozzarella, Parmigiano Reggiano, Truffle Oil
Really liked the portobello mushroom but a little sad that there was no fresh truffle but honestly can’t be complaining at this price point. The mushroom taste is quite strong which may not suit those that don’t really like the taste of shrooms. 
―
𝐏𝐮𝐥𝐥𝐞𝐝 𝐏𝐨𝐫𝐤 - $𝟏𝟕
Pork Shoulder, Bulgogi, Fior di Latte, Kimchi, Pineapple, Fig Chutney, Grana Padano
This was a rather interesting pizza and probably the most unique one out of the bunch. Unfortunately the pork shoulder and bulgogi was a little too sweet for my taste and wasn’t a really big fan of this oops. 
―
𝐂𝐚𝐥𝐚𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐢 𝐑𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬 - $𝟏𝟐
Nice crispy calamari rings with tomato sauce. I believe their tomato sauce is homemade and I really liked the sauce haha
―
Saw this place when I visited Old Hen last time and actually I think both stalls share the same space! I think the concept of Chooby can be seen through their menu and the design of the space - fuss free and minimalist. There aren’t too many different flavours and items on the menu and the interior of the place has a rather minimalist and monochrome design which I do appreciate. Really liked their pizza and I guess the comparison would be Blue Label which I absolutely liked as well. A little less fancy, not as special in terms of flavours but still amazing pizzas and a really nice place to hang! :) 
▸ 
𝟒/𝟓

📍 Fort Canning
▸
𝐁𝐫𝐨𝐧𝐭𝐞 𝐏𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐨 & 𝐇𝐢𝐦𝐚𝐥𝐚𝐲𝐚𝐧 𝐏𝐢𝐧𝐤 𝐒𝐚𝐥𝐭 
First time trying a pistachio ice cream with a slight twist. The pistachio ice cream itself was really good, nutty and creamy. Again, the only thing I wished was different would be actual pistachio nuts 😩 The salt added an interesting flavour that could help balance out the flavour if it was too intense for you but personally I think I would prefer this without the salt haha 
―
𝐂𝐨𝐥𝐨𝐦𝐛𝐢𝐚𝐧 𝐂𝐨𝐥𝐝 𝐁𝐫𝐞𝐰 & 𝐂𝐨𝐨𝐤𝐢𝐞 𝐁𝐮𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐁𝐢𝐭𝐬
This flavour looked really interesting and after trying the cold brew flavour at Nom Gelato, I will always be open to try coffee flavours. This one was pretty good too , na slight tinge of sweetness and not overly acidic. Not a fan of the cookie butter bits, didn’t feel like it went super well with the ice cream oops 😬
―
𝐓𝐨𝐤𝐲𝐨 𝐌𝐨𝐜𝐡𝐢 𝐖𝐚𝐟𝐟𝐥𝐞 - $𝟕
My second time getting ice cream with this mochi waffle and w er really liked it! It was soft and chewy and I think went really well with their ice cream. But towards the end, it got a little too soggy after all the ice cream melted so try to finish this fast before the ice cream melts! 
―
My second time here and I really like the space here, it is pretty spacious and I think it used to be 2 stalls combined. They have some pretty interesting flavours and probably a good option for desserts if you have dinner at Robertson Quay! 
▸ 
𝟑.𝟓/𝟓

📍 Robertson Quay
▸
𝐂𝐡𝐨𝐫𝐢𝐳𝐨 & 𝐁𝐞𝐞𝐟 𝐁𝐫𝐢𝐬𝐤𝐞𝐭 𝐓𝐚𝐜𝐨 - $𝟏𝟎
This was a pretty massive taco and the fillings were really generous. Came with spicy pork chorizo, braised beef brisket, red cabbage, chipotle salsa. Not a  big fan of the spicy pork chorizo but the brisket was pretty tender but I would have hoped that it would be a little more juicy 😬
―
𝐒𝐭𝐞𝐚𝐤 𝐓𝐚𝐜𝐨 - $𝟏𝟏
Came with chargrilled angus rib-eye, green chili chimichurri, burnt onion crema, pico de gallo. I really liked the steak, it was very juicy and tender. Each bite was really flavourful and I really liked this! 
―
𝐓𝐫𝐢𝐨 - 𝐂𝐡𝐢𝐩𝐬, 𝐆𝐮𝐚𝐜, 𝐒𝐚𝐥𝐬𝐚 - $𝟏𝟑
Nothing too special I guess, decent guac and salsa but not too sure if this is worth $13 🤔
―
𝐅𝐫𝐨𝐳𝐞𝐧 𝐋𝐢𝐦𝐞 𝐌𝐚𝐠𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐚 - $𝟏𝟏 (𝐡𝐚𝐩𝐩𝐲 𝐡𝐨𝐮𝐫)
Nahhh this was really diluted and couldn’t really taste much alcohol but I guess this is pretty expected for happy hour drinks. 
―
I really liked the vibes and ambiance of this place, right beside the river which is honestly damn dirty haha. The food was pretty good but I do think it is on the pricier side … for about $10 for one taco. I do think their tacos are slightly better than Papi’s but I probably don’t think it is very worth haha. There are some cheaper alternatives like Muschachos!
▸

💌 Described as a love letter to India, @superfirangi was a delicious adventure for me. The essence of their menu is based on Indian flavours, but also infused with other influences. 
.
Of course I needed to have the prata waffle with Madras fried chicken and Makhani (creamy tomato based) sauce 😛 So good, I wanted more prata to mop up the sauce 😂
.
Their ‘This is not Aloo Gobi’ has cauliflower cous cous, masala and crispy potato. My eyes widened when I took my first bite. Flavours all goes so well together! It can be a bit rich, but it’s good for sharing. Their Iberico pork was very well done too, very soft.
.
Not pictured but their chutneys, served with warm Papads and crackers were super addictive 😍 We also had Bombay Elote (grilled baby corn), garlic naan and a mashed potato. So full that we didn’t have space for dessert so I definitely want to come back and try more of their small plates because everything is something new for me 🥰
.

Heard good reviews of these brownie bars, and I have to agree that they are a real treat 🤍 The brownie bars are presented in a beautiful gift box, and each bar is also individually boxed. There are 3 varieties:
- Miss Flaky Matcha ($28) is not too sweet, and the green tea flavour comes through very well 🍵
- Mr Witty Walnut ($20) is perfect for classic chocolate fudge and walnut lovers. It’s decadent and rich and I love it 🍫
- Madam Cheeze ($24) is a chocolate brownie bar coated with luscious cream cheese and topped with strawberries 🍓 Probably the sweetest of the 3 because of the cream cheese, but still enjoyably so. 
.
All the flavours are fabulous, can definitely recommend! Thank you @howscatering for sending these over 💗😄
.

I remember this delicious chicken rice well as Justin brought me here for lunch last year! 😀 Now, Chatterbox’s iconic chicken rice is served in its own little wooden tray, but beyond the cute presentation, what makes this a fine-dining dish is the high quality of ingredients and techniques used to cook this.
.
The chicken meat is juicy and very tender, while the rice is fragrant and tasty without being oily. In fact, it’s actually still quite fluffy! The dish also comes with a warm comforting bowl of soup made with essence of chicken. Of course, the must-have condiments accompany it: chilli sauce, ginger puree and dark soya sauce.
.
Chatterbox will reopen on 14 March in a brand new space that’s dressed in calm, soothing colours. 😌
.

Yay more good food is coming to the west 😘 Nam Sing Hokkien Fried Mee from Old Airport Road has now opened a new stall closer to my home! Their recipe which has been passed down three generations, uses thin bee hoon together with the yellow noodles. They also soak the noodles in the seafood broth before frying. Yummy! Thank you for helping keeping our SG hawker food culture alive 🌟
.
Try it at Blk 177 Get Together Coffeeshop Bukit Batok West Ave 8

Indulge in the taste of home-cooked nostalgia with this 𝗗𝗿𝘆 𝗠𝗲𝗲 𝗦𝗶𝗮𝗺 from Lindle @lindle.sg ! 🥢 Finally found the opportunity to order since @samlivestoeat recommended this on her feed last year! Auntie Linda's mee siam goreng really impresses with its full-bodied flavours. It leans towards the sweeter side initially, but once you squeeze in the lime and add their homemade chilli for the extra kick, the overall flavour becomes more well-balanced.⁣
⁣
Having helped my mama with prepping the filling and cutting the wrapper during the CNY period, Bb can appreciate the amount of time & effort that goes into making these ngoh hiang! Each chunk of meat roll is juicy and well-flavoured, with the water chestnuts adding crunch to the overall texture. Bb's mama said next time must buy their ngoh hiang again. 👍🏻⁣
.⁣⁣
📦Check out @lindle.sg for more order details~⁣
.⁣⁣
.⁣

Bready to start the day with 𝗧𝗼𝗮𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗘𝗴𝗴𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝘁 from Heap Seng Leong 協勝隆 @heapsengleong! Felt like I was transported back to the 80s with the old school vibes here, from the vintage furniture to the uncle preparing the toast and coffee over a traditional charcoal fire. ⁣
⁣
Can't go wrong with the holy trinity of kaya butter toast, soft boiled eggs and tea (or kopi gu yu, whichever works for you). The charcoal-grilled toast here is so THICC and fluffy, with a thick slab of butter & reddish orange kaya slathered in between. Honestly, I preferred this to the crispier, thinner variant that is more commonly found nowadays. Also appreciate that the uncle scraped away the burnt ends from each toast! The soft boiled eggs were also large and fresh, and Bb loves mixing in the dark sauce and a dash of pepper before dipping the toast in! 🍞⁣
⁣
P.S. While here, get yourself an epok epok at $1 apiece. No photos cos Bb was hungry and ate it lol. ⁣
.⁣
📍 Address: 10 North Bridge Rd, #01-5109, Singapore 190010⁣
.⁣
.⁣

description:
This BCM from Blue Star Fishball Mushroom Minced Meat Noodle is legit underrated! Upsized their dry 𝗦𝗶𝗴𝗻𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲 𝗡𝗼𝗼𝗱𝗹𝗲 for an additional $1 & it came with a large serving of ingredients (fishballs, meatballs, minced meat, fish dumplings and braised mushrooms) atop a mountain of noodles! For $6, this was an absolute bargain given the generous portions. 🍜⁣
⁣
Noodles were QQ and laced with a well-balanced mixture of vinegar and chilli. Love that the fishballs were springy and fresh without a fishy taste, but BB's favourite was the pork liver! Some places tend to overcook the liver or has that pungent irony flavour, but the pork liver here was poached to the right consistency. 10/10 would eat again, especially since they are one of the stalls that remain open late at night. 👍🏻⁣
.⁣
📍 Address: 6 Tanjong Pagar Plaza, #02-29, Singapore 081006⁣
.⁣
.⁣

description:
Weekend dates are for feasting! Spoilt for choice at Yishun Park Hawker Center once again (seems to be the theme whenever we are here LOL) and settled upon JIAO CAI Hotplate BBQ @jiaocaiseafood for dinner! If you love stingray wings, their 𝗛𝗼𝘁 𝗣𝗹𝗮𝘁𝗲 𝗦𝗮𝗺𝗯𝗮𝗹 𝗦𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗿𝗮𝘆 ($12/15/18) will absolutely spice up your life! The chunky slab of stingray was succulent & well-barbequed with a tinge of smokiness, and the generous slather of sambal atop was an absolute knockout with a fiery punch! ⁣
 ⁣
Their 𝗦𝘄𝗲𝗲𝘁 & 𝗦𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗣𝗼𝗿𝗸 was decent as well! The sauce was well-balanced with the sweetness from sugar plus the tangy ketchup and sharp rice vinegar. We also love that the fried pork chunks were meaty and coated with a thin batter! ⁣
.⁣
📍 Address: Yishun Park Hawker Center, 51 Yishun Ave 11, #01-39, Singapore 768867⁣
.⁣
.⁣

TGIF! Lunch today was 𝗦𝘁𝗲𝗮𝗺𝗲𝗱 𝗖𝗵𝗶𝗰𝗸𝗲𝗻 𝗥𝗶𝗰𝗲 dabaoed from Nan Heng Hainanese Chicken Rice at Bukit Merah Central Food Centre. 🐔🍚 While their steamed chicken does not have the gelatinous skin that BB would die for, the meat was plump and tender without the chicken smell. The soy sauce mix that was drizzled on the meat brought out the chicken’s natural flavours well. Rice was fluffy and flavourful without being too oily, and BB loves mixing in the chilli and dark sauce to go along with the chicken! The chilli was sufficiently garlicky and veered towards the tangy side. Surprisingly, the heat was tolerable for BB (who has a low spice tolerance), so some people might not find it spicy enough for their liking LOL. Nevertheless, this is one chicken rice I would return to if I am in the area.⁣
⁣
Wishing everyone a good weekend ahead~⁣
.⁣
📍 Address: Bukit Merah Central, #02-28 163, Singapore 150163⁣

Wasn’t that hungry and wanted something light and so I ended up ordering just a simple roast chicken croissant @coexistcoffee.co .  Simple and straightforward, it was a regular chicken mayo croissant.  The croissant itself was very flaky and layered although I thought it could be more buttery.  The cafe itself was lovely with its pretty blue colour and wavy design and reminded me very much of the sea and beach 🏝 or the desert and blue skies (again nicer than their new branch 🧐).
fullName: This Is Why I’m Fat And Broke

description: With everyone flocking to @coexistcoffee.co ‘s newest outlet at LLC in Paya Lebar, their other outlet in Keong Saik is less crowded and easier to reserve.  The coffee here is also lovely, in fact, I think it’s better here.  The coffee may taste similar but the art and the coffee cup both nicer here 😁
fullName: This Is Why I’m Fat And Broke

description:
Hokkaido Puff ~ I think that’s what this is called.  Anyways, this was my surprise find from our nearby bakery cafe @thekazocafe_sg !  I was surprised it cost only like $3 or something for this giant puff that was bigger than my doggo’s head!  In fact, the puff filled up the whole plastic container! 

Not only was this very reasonably priced, but upon tasting, I found this to be so pillowy light! I mean it was crisp on the outside but still super light as a puff!  I thought it tasted like a very light polo bun but with a generous amount of light cream.  I enjoyed this pretty much and found it rather comparable to the other famous fist sized cream puff from the Hokkaido coffee chain, except this was at a more affordable price!
fullName: This Is Why I’m Fat And Broke

One of our highlights this week was dining in at Cafe Football ⚽️ Located in PUB Recreation Centre, this restaurant has an awesome Football theme which captures the essence of football by bringing football fans and foodies together 🤩 They have happy hour going on from Mon to Fri 4-7pm, with draught beers going at $10 per pint 😜 🍻
.
It was tough choosing from their extensive East meets West menu as everything looked so good 🥺 We finally decided on Crayfish Horfun and Fish and Chips for our mains.
.
The Crayfish Horfun was our personal favourite. A generous portion of silky hor fun was served with two halves of a crayfish, prawns and squid. The crayfish was succulent and juicy, and we really loved how the fresh seafood complemented the umami rich sauce. Definitely a must-try here!
.
Bring along a mate if you would like to try the Fish and Chips. Two huge fillet of battered snapper served alongside crispy truffle fries and a generous portion of salad is guaranteed to satisfy your hunger. It's quite rare to see fish and chips being served with fresh lettuce, so I would give this a big thumbs up 👍 
.
Le husband really loves the honey glazed chicken and he couldn't stop raving about it 🥲 The chicken pieces were juicy and tender, coated in a glaze that was akin to those Korean chicken. There were some pieces of garlic cloves at the bottom which attests to the authenticity of the garlic soy sauce flavour.
.
We ended our meal with a sweet dessert. The waffles were served hot and crispy, drizzled with honey and chocolate sauce 😋
.
Thanks Irene at @cafefootballsg for the immaculate service and tour, we really loved our meal today and will definitely be back again with friends for happy hour 🤩🤩
.
The ANTicipated scale ⚖ 
👅Flavour: Overall 8 ants
💰Value: 8 ants 
📍Convenience: 8 ants

BRB drooling over this fine piece of work!!! Always passed by Lad & Dad and finally got the chance to try the crowd's favourite fish and chips and scotch eggs.
.
We couldn't resist trying the Scotch Egg ($12). The soft boiled egg was wrapped in a hearty pork sausage meat and covered in glorious golden bread crumbs sitting atop purple slaw.  As usual, this was gone within seconds despite taking small bites of it at a time 🥵
.
We also shared a large serving of Fish and Chips ($28). The beer battered atlantic haddock fish indeed lived up to our expectations - the silky smooth flesh was firm yet flaky, encased within a golden crispy light batter. For the sides, we really love the crispy thick cut chips that were seasoned well 😋 Drizzled Heinz malted vinegar over the dish which had the right amount of acidity cutting gently through the crispy, fried texture.
.
The ANTicipated scale ⚖ 
👅Flavour: Overall 8 ants
💰Value: 7 ants
📍Convenience: 7 ants

Flutes Restaurant indeed lives up to their name of being an award-winning fine dining European restaurant. We tried out their Valentine's Day menu ($98+) and really loved the prompt service and lovely ambience.
.
Ranking the food in order of flavours, our favourite dish has got to be the Barbequed Wanderer Barley Fed Beef Striploin. We opted for medium rare, and was treated with a super juicy and tender meat. Served together with Jerusalem artichoke and asparagus, I found it interesting that they used hazelnut and sauce perigord which added an extra nutty dimension to the overall flavour profile 🤤
.
The Pan-fried Foie Gras was an absolute gastronomic delight!!! It was served warmed, topped with caramelised Sarawak pineapple, chocolate and coriander. The pairing might seem strange, but the rich umami flavour totally blew us away :") So glad that we opted to top up $22 for this.
.
We were pretty impressed with the Carpaccio of Robbins Island Wagyu. It looks stunning on the plate with thinly sliced wagyu beef garnished with huitlacoche mustard, black truffle and grissini. The buttery texture was just *chefs kiss* 🤤
.
Have always been curious about the foam technique used in Top Chef, and we finally tried shellfish foam that complemented the Roasted Skull Island Prawn. The lobster oil added a fragrant touch that made us wolf this down within seconds.
.
Another lovely dish was the Snapper Fillet. The truffled chicken essence, with its totally complex flavours, nicely enhanced the flavour of the fried sweet snapper flesh.
.
It was our first time trying Paris-Brest, which consisted of crispy choux pastry and a praline flavoured cream with Kirsch Cherry. Being a decadent sweet dessert, it definitely appealed to my sweet tooth 🥵
.
Unfortunarely, there was nothing much to shout about for the South Australian Lobster ‘Lasksa Noodles’. The portion was quite small for a top up at 22+ 🥲
.
The ANTicipated scale ⚖ 
👅Flavour: Overall 7.5 ants
💰Value: 8 ants
📍Convenience: 7 ants

The Brewing Ground has been on my cafe list since forever, and we finally travelled down to Joo Chiat to give it a try. Located within an old school compound, we absolutely love the chill vibes here and their decor is just 💯! Although the prices were on the higher side, the portions were huge and their coffee was pretty decent as well.
.
The Crab & Signature Scrambled Eggs On Toast ($25) looked really appetising with sautéed crabmeat and ikura sitting atop a slice of sourdough. Sad to say, I wasn't a huge fan of the taste as it tasted rather acidic and funky for my liking 🤣 
.
The Breakfast Burger ($20) fared a little better in my opinion, which was a "zenged up" version of Macs sausage egg mcmuffin. The pork sausage patty complemented the silky scrambled eggs and caramelized onions. Also loved the brioche buns which were grilled perfectly😋
.
We were also intrigued by the Cod Fish & Chips ($20) which had a crispy batter and firm flesh encased within. Would have preferred the meat to be more buttery and flaky.
.
The ANTicipated scale ⚖ 
👅Flavour: 6.5 ants
💰Value: 7 ants
📍Convenience: 6.5 ants

Wowzers this weekend has been fulfilling!! Stumbled upon a hidden gem at Sen of Japan, and we were pretty impressed with the quality of the food. Furthermore, we also used Burpple Beyond for their mains which made it all the more worthwhile. The portions might seem small but we really savoured every bite and it was a good meal with a hot sake to pair dem dishes with 🤤
.
The Black Cod Soy is a velvety and flaky soy-glazed black cod fillet that's marinated well with Hiro’s special soy marinade. The glaze tasted distinctively of soy sauce and something sweet like honey(?) which combined smoothly with the rich, savory soy sauce. 
 .
The Uni Pasta was our second favourite 🥺 So very creamy and fresh, the uni had a subtle yet pleasant sweetness to it. The pasta was also topped with sakura ebi, ikura and truffle mushroom cream sauce that made each bite fragrant and simply stunning!! Just wish that there was more uni to pair the pasta with 🥵
.
We were also won over by their Anago Tempura ($20) which is saltwater eel tempura that had a light and crisp batter encasing sweet and delicate eel meat.
.
Last but not least, we didn't forget our greens! Got the Inaniwa Salad ($19) which is a mixed salad with chilled inaniwa udon noodle, crab meat, prawns and golden miso dressing. Love the sweet umami combination of this.
.
The ANTicipated scale ⚖ 
👅Flavour: 7.5 ants
💰Value: 7 ants
📍Convenience: 7 ants

@cakecornersco_'s mochis are fluffy, soft and generously filled, seriously one of the best mochis we've had in a long time!✨☺️💛 Their special mochi box had a more modern flavors while the fruity box (our personal fav!!) had more of a traditional mochi taste, BOTH are so good and most importantly not too sweet at all!👌🏻🙏🏻 Here are their available flavors: ⁣
⁣

🌟 Choco lava⁣
⁣

Mango Blueberry yoghurt⁣
⁣

Matcha Pistachio Babka✨🍵🥰🤎💚
⁣
The babka was crisp and dense (in a good way! it didn't fall apart as you take a bite☺️) it had a deep and aromatic earthy flavor, the matcha flavor was quite strong and paired with perfectly roasted pistachio 🤤🤤 We noticed that a really unique part of @bakesbymabs's bakes is that they are not sweet at all, it's a really fine balance between subtle sweetness and bitterness👌🏻🤎💯⁣
⁣
Aside from the Babka, they also sent over a box of their Tea Series Macarons, similar to the Babka, the flavor profile of the macarons are rich and earthy, the texture is really nice as well! 🥰 ⁣
⁣
Tea Series Macarons ($15 for 6 pieces): ⁣

Vietnamese Rice Noodle Salad🇻🇳🥰🌿
⁣
@qwangsg aims to serve Vietnamese Rice Noodle Salads with a Healthier Twist!✨🌟 We tried out their Pork and Chicken bowls and we absolutely loved it! We really enjoyed how clean they tasted and yet still quite filling and definitely has that authentic Vietnamese taste 🤤 ⁣
⁣
All their bowls are: ⁣
❌ No MSG⁣
❌ No oil⁣
❌ Less sugar, salt⁣
⁣
We also had their Vietnamese coffee which is SO GOOD👌🏻🙌🏻 It was aromatic, rich in flavor and so fragrant without being too sweet, it's the perfect beverage to go along with either of the bowls! 10/10 would recommend!!! 🥰⁣
⁣
Enjoy authentic Vietnamese tastes and flavours that's delicious and equally great for your body! 🧡 Head over to @qwangsg and place your orders now! And be sure to use their new promo code - ‘1FOR1’ at checkout! 🤎⁣

Artisanal Tart✨🥰🧚🏻‍♀️🌺🧡💫⁣
⁣
These would have to be the most beautiful tarts we've laid our eyes on, just look at them! 😍🥰 Founded by the Masterchef Asia finalist Sandrian Tan, The Tartlery aims to reinvent the humble tart✨ These tarts are indeed elevated not only in terms of their complex flavor combis but also in their presentation👌🏻🙌🏻 10/10 would definitely be a highlight for any special occasion 💯⁣
⁣
Our favorites would have to be the Samsara✨ A creation inspired by the Himalayas, white chocolate, candied ginger, exotic saffron custard and a pinch of cardamon, such a unique flavor with subtle nodes of spices, it's so so good 🥰⁣
⁣
We tried out their Box of 6: ⁣

🌟 Apple and Rhubarb⁣
🌟 Samsara⁣
🌟 Cherry Choco Hazel ⁣
🌟 Pineapple Tart ⁣
⁣

❤️😋 Delicious Mee Siam in Bedok (S$3). Saw a queue for this and decided to give it a try.

Taste different from the usual Mee Siam. Gravy is light orange in color.

This is Chinese style #meesiam . I like the gravy! It's light, not too sweet, not really spicy (which i prefer) and there's some tanginess from the lime.

Comes with a full egg, a piece of tau pok, beans sprouts and some chilli. What's different is that they boil the bee hoon instead of stir-frying, so its not oily.

Recommended 👍

Wholesome meal at an affordable price! Will eat this again when i want something healthy 🌿😊.

The iconic @chatterboxsg Mandarin Chicken Rice! Proudly served since 1971, this dish has been synonymous with the restaurant name and enjoyed by many along the years! Using only chickens that weigh ~2kg each, Executive Chef Liew uses a unique ‘steam-cook’ method to obtain consistently succulent and juicy chicken. The individual set comes with fluffy & fragrant chicken rice cooked with specially-procured aged Jasmine rice and a trinity of chicken fat, shallots and pandan leaves, a proprietary chilli sauce with a fresh and spicy kick, grated ginger, dark soy sauce, and a bowl of chicken broth. $25 for Individual Set, $38 for Half Chicken, $72 for Whole Chicken.

Come 14 March 2022, this well-loved local restaurant will mark a grand return in a beautiful new space on level five of the newly-minted Hilton Orchard. Swipe for some snippets of the interior!
